To add a 60% transparency to an image you are using with `next/image`, you need to apply the `opacity` CSS style to the wrapping `div` or apply it directly to the `Image` component via the `className`. An opacity value of `0.4` will result in 60% transparency (since 100% - 60% = 40%, and opacity is defined from 0 to 1).

However, when trying to apply styles directly on the `Image` component, note that Next.js applies some styles and elements on top of the image which can interfere with certain CSS properties, like `className`. To be certain your styles apply as you intend, it's often best to target the container. Here's an updated version of your `Bulb` component that applies 60% transparency to the image:

```javascript
import Image from "next/image";

const Bulb = () => {
  return (
    <div className="absolute -left-36 -bottom-12 rotate-12 bg-blend-difference animate-pulse duration-75 z-10 w-[200px] xl:w-[260px] select-none pointer-events-none opacity-40">
      <Image
        src="/bulb.png"
        alt="bulb"
        width={260}
        height={200}
        className="w-full h-full"
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default Bulb;
```

In this snippet, the `opacity-40` class has been added to the `div`, which will result in the image appearing with 60% transparency. The `opacity-40` class corresponds to the utility classes provided by Tailwind CSS (if you are using it), which would apply an opacity of 0.4 to the element, hence making it 60% transparent. If you are not using Tailwind CSS or a similar utility-first CSS framework, you might need to define this CSS yourself:

```css
.opacity-40 {
  opacity: 0.4;
}
```

Add this CSS rule to your stylesheet, and ensure that it's being imported into your component or your global styles.

Remember to adjust the pixel values for `width` and `height` properties in the `Image` tag if needed to match the size of your image or design specification.

