Here is how to adjust your `ProjectsBtn` component using conditional rendering with state hooks in React to achieve the hover effect:

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import Image from 'next/image';
import Link from 'next/link';

import { HiArrowRight } from 'react-icons/hi2';

const ProjectsBtn = () => {
  const [isHovered, setIsHovered] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div className="mx-auto xl:mx-0"
         onMouseEnter={() => setIsHovered(true)}
         onMouseLeave={() => setIsHovered(false)}>
      <Link
        href="/designs"
        className="relative w-[185px] h-[185px] flex justify-center items-center bg-circleStar bg-cover bg-center bg-no-repeat"
      >
        <Image
          src="/black.gif"
          alt="rounded text"
          width={185}
          height={185}
          className="bg-cover animate-pulse w-full h-full max-w-[141px] max-h-[148px] pointer-events-none select-none"
        />
        {isHovered ? (
          <span
            className="absolute text-end"
            style={{ color: '#f13024', fontWeight: 'bold' }}
          >
            DESIGNS
          </span>
        ) : (
          <HiArrowRight
            className="text-4xl text-start transition-all duration-300"
            style={{ color: '#f13024' }}
            aria-hidden="true"
          />
        )}
      </Link>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ProjectsBtn;
```

In this code, I've introduced a React state hook called `isHovered` to track the hover state. The `onMouseEnter` and `onMouseLeave` are event handlers that update `isHovered`. When `isHovered` is `true` (when the mouse is over the element), the "DESIGNS" text is displayed. When `isHovered` is `false` (when the mouse is not over the element), the arrow is displayed instead.

This method doesn't require any additional CSS for showing or hiding the elements based on hover and is totally controlled within your React component. Remember, React's `useState` and the `onMouseEnter`/`onMouseLeave` event handlers come from React, so ensure that you are correctly importing `useState` from the React package as shown in the example above.

The placement of the `HiArrowRight` icon within the `<div>` is controlled by the CSS classes and styles that you apply. Based on the provided code snippet, the class `text-start` applied to the `HiArrowRight` icon could be causing it to align to the left. Also, since the icon is absolutely positioned, its location within its containing element will be influenced by any `top`, `right`, `bottom`, or `left` styles you apply, as well as the positioning of the parent element.

To center the arrow horizontally within the `<div>`, make sure your parent `<div>` is styled to handle absolute positioning correctly. Here is an updated snippet to ensure the arrow is centered:

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import Image from 'next/image';
import Link from 'next/link';

import { HiArrowRight } from 'react-icons/hi2';

const ProjectsBtn = () => {
  const [isHovered, setIsHovered] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div className="mx-auto xl:mx-0 group"
         onMouseEnter={() => setIsHovered(true)}
         onMouseLeave={() => setIsHovered(false)}>
      <Link
        href="/designs"
        className="relative w-[185px] h-[185px] flex justify-center items-center bg-circleStar bg-cover bg-center bg-no-repeat"
        aria-label="View designs"
      >
        <Image
          src="/black.gif"
          alt="rounded text"
          width={185}
          height={185}
          className="bg-cover animate-pulse w-full h-full max-w-[141px] max-h-[148px] pointer-events-none select-none"
        />
        {isHovered ? (
          <span
            className="absolute inset-x-0 top-1/2 -translate-y-1/2 text-center"
            style={{ color: '#f13024', fontWeight: 'bold' }}
          >
            DESIGNS
          </span>
        ) : (
          <HiArrowRight
            className="absolute inset-x-0 top-1/2 -translate-y-1/2 text-4xl transition-all duration-300"
            style={{ color: '#f13024' }}
          />
        )}
      </Link>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ProjectsBtn;
```

In this snippet, I've removed the `text-start` class from `HiArrowRight` since it's not appropriate when you want to center the icon. For both the `HiArrowRight` icon and the "DESIGNS" span, I've added `absolute inset-x-0 top-1/2` classes to center them horizontally and `translate-y-1/2` to center them vertically. `inset-x-0` applies `left: 0` and `right: 0`, which combined with `text-center` on the span helps center the content. The `top-1/2` will place the item's top edge in the middle vertically, and `-translate-y-1/2` will then pull it back up by half its own height to center it vertically in its parent.

If you aren't using Tailwind CSS, you would accomplish the same by adding relevant CSS styles manually:

```css
.centered {
  /* Centering horizontally */
  position: absolute;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);

  /* Centering vertically */
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
}
```

Please note, if you're not using Tailwind CSS, adjust the classes accordingly and ensure that your CSS rules are defined and imported correctly in your project.

